We start by extracting and computing the totals from the end‐of‐period balances (unless noted otherwise):

1. Operating Cash Flow Ratio 
 • Operating Cash Flow = –1,182,491.05  
 • Current Liabilities (Accounts Payable + Taxes Payable) = 302,000.00 + 197,821.72 = 499,821.72  
 • Ratio = –1,182,491.05 ÷ 499,821.72 ≈ –2.37

2. Cash Flow to Debt Ratio 
 • (In the example the “debt” used was the current liabilities; hence we use the same base.)  
 • Ratio = –1,182,491.05 ÷ 499,821.72 ≈ –2.37

3. Inventory Turnover Ratio 
 • Defined as Cost of Goods Sold ÷ Average Inventory  
 • In our case, Inventory is 0 at both beginning and end so the average inventory is (0 + 0)/2 = 0.  
 • With a non-zero COGS (1,684,000.00), the ratio is mathematically undefined. In practice, if no inventory is held the inventory turnover may be considered “infinite”.  
 • We will report this as "Infinity".

4. Debt to Equity Ratio 
 • Total Liabilities = 499,821.72 (the only liabilities listed)  
 • Total Owner’s Equity = 14,390,936.99  
 • Ratio = 499,821.72 ÷ 14,390,936.99 ≈ 0.0347, which we round to 0.03

5. Quick Ratio 
 • Quick Assets include cash, bank deposits, interest receivable and accounts receivable.  
  ○ Cash on Hand = 2,103,508.95  
  ○ Bank Deposits = 4,714,000.00  
  ○ Interest Receivable = 15,414.09  
  ○ Accounts Receivable = 3,149,338.94  
 • Total Quick Assets = 2,103,508.95 + 4,714,000.00 + 15,414.09 + 3,149,338.94 = 9,982,261.98  
 • Quick Ratio = 9,982,261.98 ÷ 499,821.72 ≈ 19.96

6. Current Ratio  
 • Current Assets (given) = 9,982,261.98  
 • Current Liabilities = 499,821.72  
 • Current Ratio = 9,982,261.98 ÷ 499,821.72 ≈ 19.96

Thus, we summarize our answers as follows:
